ORA bar plot:
The barplot of ORA results confirmed cytoplasmic translation as the most gene-rich enriched pathway with 15 contributing genes, followed by metabolic pathways including energy derivation by oxidation of organic compounds and generation of precursor metabolites and energy each contributing 13 genes, and oxidative phosphorylation, aerobic respiration and cellular respiration each contributing 12 genes. Synaptic pathways including translation at presynaptic, synaptic and postsynaptic compartments each contributed approximately 11 genes. The consistent enrichment of both metabolic and synaptic pathways across both visualization methods confirms the biological robustness of these findings, suggesting that peak IAV infection at D08 induces coordinated transcriptional changes in neuronal energy metabolism and synaptic function in cluster 0 of the nasal mucosa.

ORA enrichment plot:
Over-representation analysis of significant differentially expressed genes from cluster 0 between Naive and D08 timepoints revealed enrichment of two major biological themes. The most significantly enriched pathway was cytoplasmic translation, showing the highest gene ratio and gene count, suggesting altered protein synthesis between timepoints. Additional metabolic pathways including oxidative phosphorylation, aerobic respiration, cellular respiration and mitochondrial ATP synthesis were significantly enriched, consistent with the elevated mitochondrial gene expression observed in the volcano plot and suggesting increased cellular energy demands in neuronal cells during peak infection at D08. Neuronal functional pathways including translation at synaptic compartments, neurotransmitter transport and secretion, and synaptic vesicle cycling were also enriched, consistent with the neuronal identity of cluster 0 and reflecting altered synaptic activity during IAV infection of the nasal mucosa. These findings suggest that peak influenza infection at D08 induces metabolic and synaptic transcriptional changes in olfactory neurons, potentially contributing to the olfactory dysfunction associated with respiratory viral infection.

